# Git Workflow

**Never push directly to `main`.** No exceptions â€” not even one-liners or typo fixes.

## Required Workflow

```bash
# 1. Branch off main
git checkout main && git pull origin main
git checkout -b <type>/<short-description>

# 2. Make changes, commit
git add -A
git commit -m "<type>: <description>"

# 3. Run checks before pushing (see post-change-checks rule)
bun run typecheck && trunk check --fix && bun test

# 4. Push and open PR
git push origin <branch>
gh pr create --base main --title "..." --body "..."
```

## Branch Naming

| Type | When |
| --- | --- |
| `feature/` | New functionality |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/` | Docs, deps, config, refactoring |

## Why

CI deploys on push to `main`. Unreviewed changes go straight to production.
PRs give a chance to catch issues before they affect the daily briefing.
